<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════
     ACT II · CONTEXT — the consulting bottleneck
     ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="sp2-stakes">
  <div class="sp2-stakes-inner">
    <div class="sp2-stakes-layout">
      <div class="sp2-stakes-stats">
        <div class="sp2-stakes-hero-stat">
          <span class="val">200+</span>
          <span class="label">Organizations</span>
        </div>
        <div class="sp2-stakes-supporting">
          <div class="stat"><span class="val">200K</span><span class="label">Leaders assessed</span></div>
          <div class="stat"><span class="val">40</span><span class="label">Countries</span></div>
          <div class="stat"><span class="val">50K+</span><span class="label">Taylor DB</span></div>
          <div class="stat"><span class="val">6</span><span class="label">Tools shipped</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="sp2-stakes-context">
        <h2>Culture consulting was <span class="accent">analog</span>.<br/>Assessments took <span class="accent">weeks</span>.<br/>Results arrived on PDFs.</h2>
        <p>Walking the Talk measured culture for Visa, Vodafone, Telstra, Westpac, Tesco Bank, eBay, Experian, Syngenta, Takeda, and Lilly. Their consultants were the best in the world at what they did — and they were the bottleneck. Every assessment needed a consultant to run it, compile it, and deliver it.</p>
        <p>The firm wanted its practice to scale without its people scaling linearly with it. That meant building the software layer underneath — tools a CHRO could run herself, get results from in minutes, and use in the boardroom the same week.</p>
        <p><strong>Six tools shipped. Fortune 500s self-serving. Acquisition followed.</strong></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

