<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════
     ACT III · THE STORY — five chapters
     ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="sp2-story">
  <div class="sp2-story-inner">
    <div class="sp2-story-head">
      <h2>The Story</h2>
      <p>From consulting-only assessments to a software suite Fortune 500s ran themselves.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Chapter 01 -->
    <article class="sp2-chapter">
      <div class="sp2-chapter-index">
        <span class="sp2-chapter-num">01</span>
        <span class="sp2-chapter-date">2023 · The brief</span>
      </div>
      <div class="sp2-chapter-body">
        <h3>The consultants were the bottleneck.</h3>
        <p>Walking the Talk had the methodology — the decade-old frameworks, the archetype taxonomy, the Psynet psychometric engine behind it. What they didn't have was a software layer that let clients <em>run</em> the methodology. Every assessment needed a consultant to set up, score, and present. The practice couldn't scale past the calendar of its senior people.</p>
        <p>The brief was simple and unforgiving: take the three tools the firm ran on, and make them work without a consultant in the room.</p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <!-- Chapter 02 -->
    <article class="sp2-chapter">
      <div class="sp2-chapter-index">
        <span class="sp2-chapter-num">02</span>
        <span class="sp2-chapter-date">January 2024 · Taylor Assessment</span>
      </div>
      <div class="sp2-chapter-body">
        <h3>The only psychometric in the world that measures culture contribution.</h3>
        <p>Taylor Assessment scores individual culture contribution across <strong>six archetypes and thirty behaviors</strong> — a categorization no other tool on the market captures. I redesigned it ground-up in partnership with <strong>Psynet</strong>, the psychometrics house that built the engine underneath. Every screen was a conversation between design and psychometric rigor; nothing in the assessment could bend if the math didn't allow it.</p>
        <p>The new Taylor Assessment was <strong>press-released globally in January 2024</strong>. It's now used by over 50,000 leaders in Walking the Talk's database — and it's the single tool that defined the firm's post-redesign positioning.</p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <!-- Chapter 03 -->
    <article class="sp2-chapter">
      <div class="sp2-chapter-index">
        <span class="sp2-chapter-num">03</span>
        <span class="sp2-chapter-date">2023–2024 · Culture Insights Survey</span>
      </div>
      <div class="sp2-chapter-body">
        <h3>Weeks of waiting collapsed into minutes.</h3>
        <p>Culture Insights Survey measures <strong>ninety behaviors across multiple languages</strong> — a 15-to-20-minute assessment designed to produce immediate portal results. Before the redesign, HR teams waited days or weeks for a consultant to compile data and write it up. After the redesign, a CHRO could open the portal the moment the survey closed and walk into a board meeting with findings the same afternoon.</p>
        <p>The shift wasn't cosmetic. The entire service model moved from <em>consultant-delivered</em> to <em>self-serve-with-expert-support-when-needed</em>.</p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</section>

